<p>Missouri receives excellent solar irradiance levels, with most regions experiencing between 4.2 to 5.1 peak sun hours daily. The state's solar resource is comparable to or better than many leading solar markets, with annual irradiance levels ranging from 1,400 to 1,600 kWh per square meter. Peak production typically occurs from April through September, with July and August providing the highest energy generation potential. During these peak months, a typical 6kW residential system can generate between 800-950 kWh monthly, while winter production averages 400-550 kWh per month.</p>

<p>Seasonal variations in Missouri are moderate, with summer-to-winter production ratios typically ranging from 1.8:1 to 2.2:1. This relatively stable year-round production makes solar particularly attractive for offsetting both air conditioning costs in summer and heating expenses during colder months. The state's geographic position provides consistent east-west sun exposure, and most residential installations achieve optimal performance with south-facing arrays tilted between 30-40 degrees. Even east and west-facing installations typically maintain 85-90% of optimal production levels, providing flexibility for various roof configurations.</p>

